We are on Suur-Karja Street, which should be one of Tallinn's favorite party streets only, that the street is, there are no more partygoers.
According to Juuri, who came to the old town to have fun on Saturday night, the fear of corona has scared away the partygoers, if they used to meet friends there, now it would be at home, only youth gangs hang out in front of the museum as before.
Please, please, nothing is happening.
It's a pity, a pity, that the old town is dying, slowly dying.
Riga resident Raamisson, stopping near the old town, has been watching Tallinn's weekend nightlife for three months and when the clock strikes midnight, the booze taps are turned off, then the party is over.
According to Juuri, the old town is so depressingly empty that when he tried to give white roses to passing women on Saturday night, there was so little movement on Viru Street that in half an hour of work he managed to give away eight out of twenty roses.
According to Maksim Sokolov, the owner of the couple's first pipe, on the one hand he understands the purpose of the imposed restrictions, but they have dealt a serious blow to both turnover and the number of visitors.
According to taxi driver Jevgeni, who was waiting for customers around midnight near Hollywood or the Work Club, nightlife disappeared from the old town as soon as the night-time alcohol restriction was imposed. Since then, the life of a taxi driver has been anything but golden, this Friday he was at work from eight in the morning until four in the morning and had only four customers. The old town is not completely dead yet, there seems to be life, but not our life anymore. The week is almost over, let's see what were its most important events. My experiences in the field of environment have been very intense during my time as an advisor, all environmental ministries and environmental issues have been on my table, in the Ministry of Finance, as an advisor to the Minister of Finance. The situation in the Estonian state is critical and we are clearly moving towards a health crisis. Next week, the Social Affairs Committee of the Riigikogu will again discuss the law on the provision of psychiatric aid. Psychiatrists are the only specialists that a child under eighteen needs parental permission to access. Specialists involved in the work of the commission have repeatedly pointed out the need to change the law. Ave H suddenly asked why the amendment has stalled in the Riigikogu. The gap in the law does not allow young people under eighteen to seek psychiatric help without parental permission. Although the power elite has repeatedly confirmed the need to change the law, young people continue to be left without help every month. Young people should always have the opportunity to seek help, regardless of what their family members think, so the disbelief in seeking help for mental health problems has not disappeared from all families. The current law is largely based on the situation that all children have supportive parents, a functioning family, who can then support their child and make decisions for him, unfortunately in my work in practice I see that unfortunately the situation is different, that all parents either do not know how or for some reason do not want to deal with their child's problems, if he lacks perhaps the necessary skills, he needs help himself or even causes his child's problems. The Social Affairs Committee of the Riigikogu has discussed the topic six times. Different aspects of the problem have been explained by specialists, representatives of thirty-six organizations, also signed a joint appeal, which justifies the importance of the amendment. It has been a year and a half since the Chancellor of Justice drew the state's attention to the fact that this small amendment would be fair and necessary for young people. Today we are in a situation where the Social Affairs Committee of the Riigikogu has been dealing with this topic for almost a year, including the Ministry of Education, the Ministry of Justice, the Ministry of Social Affairs, very loudly, including the Prime Minister and the Minister of Social Affairs, have expressed support for this small amendment. And we are still processing and cannot get it processed. What initially seemed like a small and simple amendment has grown into a fundamental opposition. EKRE member Urmas Espenberg, who is a member of the Social Affairs Committee, says that theoretically they agree that young people could exceptionally see a psychiatrist without parental permission. In practice, no agreement is reached. According to Espenberg, the two exceptional cases where a young person could turn to a psychiatrist without a parent are the absence of a guardian or domestic violence. I certainly do not agree that everyone will start changing their psychiatrists at will, so that every ordinary child, let him go to a psychologist's counseling first and then the psychologist will see whether, whether, what to do next. What are the opponents of the amendments afraid of? Do they not trust young people or do they not trust professionals, i.e. psychiatrists? Espenberg cites the need to work with the family, the fear that too strong drugs will be prescribed to young people, but also the fear that mental problems will become a fashion disease or that young people will start selling prescribed drugs on the black market. Young people are prone to trying all sorts of things and then, when the talk of antidepressants opens up, they may start selling them to each other. The psychiatrist refutes the fears of the opponents of the amendments, it is the doctor's task and competence to assess the patient's condition and act accordingly. It is always the doctor's wisdom to see through these situations, what are the real motives for coming and how is the use of medication, i.e. there are rules in place that prevent most of these problems. Both specialist doctors and youth workers believe the problem is serious and needs action. I turned to thirteen youth workers from four different youth organizations and a third of them have actually had encounters with the question where the child needs psychiatric help, but due to the parent's response it has not been found. I asked them for stories, the stories are mildly scary sometimes, two of these stories led to suicide attempts, fortunately unsuccessful attempts, one of them is an ongoing process where the child does not dare to contact his parents, as his parents strongly believe that mental health issues are something that is only for the insane or strongly religious.
Urmas Espemberg suggests a solution that a referral or permission to a psychiatrist could be written by another adult who interacts with young people. In practice, this looks like we have all sorts of networks, whether it's the youth and child protection network, the police where certain cases are registered, they can make a referral there, then there are school psychologists available to turn to, there are many opportunities and there are many psychologists in Estonia and they are all relatively unused, so we should think about how to solve these things, not blame each other. However, each intermediate stage increases bureaucracy and requires additional forces, currently there is a problem to meet even the existing requirements, only thirty-nine percent of Estonian schools have a psychologist at work, which means that more than half of the schools have to manage without a psychologist. Where they are, they are very good and where they are not, they are greatly missed. What happens if a person does not get help in time? Well, in the case of mental disorders, one of the most common of which is depression, there is a very high risk that it will become chronic, but before it becomes chronic, it ruins your quality of life, so the young person cannot study, cannot communicate his life, realize himself in life and he interferes with everyday life, so what initially sits at home on the computer, no longer a sausage, but there is a long one.

The number of people infected with the coronavirus exceeded the two hundred people limit on several days this week and Social Minister Tanel Kiik said on Friday that due to the spread of the coronavirus, Estonia is heading towards a health crisis. Hanneli Rudi investigated how the virus is currently spreading. Two hundred and eight, one hundred and thirty-one, two hundred and forty-one, these are not winning points in some dart game, but the numbers of people infected with the coronavirus this week, kind of sad records. Yet in mid-October, Estonia still stood out in Europe with exceptionally low infection rates. Now, however, in Tallinn and Harju County, the source of infection can no longer be identified in every second patient, i.e. the disease has started to spread secretly. Was it really predictable, but well, corona is such that it tends not to grow like a constant spread, but it goes with such sudden outbreaks, whether this of course means that things got out of hand, well, I wouldn't say that right now, that the growth rate is certainly the most fun to the east and we could get out of this growth rate, because at this growth rate we certainly won't last until spring. Such a rapid increase in morbidity is expected according to Mario Kadastik, the creator of corona models, because the infection factor R, which shows how many people one patient passes the virus on, has been between one point two and one point four for the last couple of weeks. By Saturday, this figure had risen to one point five, which means that two patients passed the infection on to three, even if the infection factor does not increase, it would be a serious threat to the Estonian health care system, because in this case the hospitals would be filled with corona patients by the end of the year. Although a lot has been said about Covid nineteen, whether there are enough controlled breathing devices for everyone, the whole medical system will actually fall into a serious crisis, according to Kadastik. And if this system now goes completely out of hand, as it has in some places in the world where hospitals are only full of Covid patients, then the problem actually arises that we can no longer treat other things that would be very treatable. Corona departments also require much more staff and therefore it is not possible to endlessly create additional beds there. According to Kadastik, efforts should be made to get the situation under control before the critical limit is reached. With the current numbers, he estimates that we can rather talk about the initial phase of a giant wave than the spread of the disease in waves. It remains with small waves until the Health Board gets most of the contacts. Well, we have been on the border for a long time and our very good inspectors of the Northern Regional Department are doing their best. Of course, the involvement of the call robot helped a lot. The call robot does read the words to close contacts, but life has shown that this is not enough, because often the robot's message is not understood. Thus, the corona detectives working in Tallinn have received about ten helpers from outside the house who call people over. Help has also come from other regional corona detectives. Can there also be a situation where you just raise your hands and give up looking for close contacts or is this scenario completely ruled out? This scenario is completely possible if we cannot control the disease, right. And, and it is very important now that we all behave correctly, because now everything is in our hands. If the power of the corona detectives fades, Kadastik does not think there is any escape from general restrictions. In any case of exponential growth, the longer this growth is, the harder it is to eliminate this situation, i.e. the sooner we can get on top of it, the less trouble we get rid of it. Kadastik recommends avoiding face-to-face communication as much as possible, keeping a distance from strangers and if this is not possible, then use a mask.
According to the scientist, it is worth remembering that the results of today's actions or restrictions will only affect the coronavirus statistics in two to four weeks' time. The government's advisory scientific council has already submitted its recommendations for restrictions. Instead of restoring the two plus two rule, they simply recommended a two-meter distancing requirement. This couple or, well, if the nightlife is closed, yes, we recommended that, or the minimum reduction, but no one is currently preventing anyone from wearing a mask in closed spaces, please people, put on a mask, does Jüri Ratas really have to tell you that? Let's now see how many of us can be affected by one person's infection. The Health Board described to us a real virus outbreak where there were an exceptionally large number of close contacts. Five hundred people ended up in isolation, many of whom had to interrupt their work for two weeks. The focus of the case is the father, as the virus traveled to Estonia with the father from abroad. The father who returned home infected his wife, son, son's partner, two daughters, and daughter's child. The infected mother worked in a care institution where she came into contact with ninety-five people. Her close contacts were tested twice, none of them fell ill. After the contacts of the son who worked in a large collective, one colleague fell ill and three hundred and sixty-five close contacts were monitored, none of whom fell ill. This infected colleague brought the infection home and five people in his family circle were infected. The son's partner worked in a food place, which was closed and fourteen contacts were sent to isolation, fortunately, no one fell ill. The daughter studying at school had twenty-one close contacts, all of whom were sent to home isolation, no one fell ill. The daughter's child's kindergarten was closed and fourteen close contacts were monitored, no one fell ill. In addition, eighteen family acquaintances were also in isolation, none of whom fell ill and as a result of this outbreak, thirteen people were infected and five hundred and twenty-seven people were in two-week isolation and under the supervision of the Health Board. As this week's news programs focused on monitoring the US presidential election, our correspondents asked who Estonian people would have preferred for this position. Who do you prefer, Trump or Biden? I think it should be newer, although older, but still newer, Biden. Generally, I am neutral, but if neither is sympathetic, but to choose between the two, then rather Biden yes. Well, Trump has already been, so it would just be a change. At the moment I have not thought through the answer for myself, but let's see what the future brings. I think, Biden. And but why? Well, he's a Democrat and his views seem more suitable to me. I don't really like this Trump, so. There have been such things with Trump that I don't like. Well, many things, many things that I see even in our politics too, that. The main concern for me is that both are relatively elderly people, that, that well, how they will endure in this hard work and difficult position. Well, I still think Biden, let's hope it gets a little calmer. Still Biden. But why? Well, why, I don't know, I don't like Trump. No, I can't say, well, Trump was a very cool guy. It doesn't matter, whoever he is. This year, during the digital culture year, the foundation was laid for the Estonian audiobook market. If, for example, in Sweden, digital and audiobooks already hold nearly half of the fiction publishing market, then in Estonia we are only taking the first steps in this direction. Reet Veidebaum went to investigate the making of audiobooks. This spring, the National Library initiated a public procurement, ordering audiobooks from fifty Estonian authors' works. Publishers, "Pegasus" Estonian book and "Good Story" created a trivial platform "Digiread", where Estonian audiobooks have been offered since August. Well, now we are reaching the first hundred and more precisely, almost seventy of them are Estonian literature and the rest are translated literature, so in total this morning I looked, there were six hundred and fifty hours, so it's about twenty days of author books. In fact, statistics from the rest of the world show that lighter genres are popular, such as entertainment literature, crime thrillers and always certain local authors. In Estonia, among others, Indrek Hargla, Teeke Melchior and the Oleviste mystery have been listened to the most. Stories by Andrus Kivirähk, Priit Kuus's ship cook brother and Armin Kõomägi, Luis Vutoon. Authors usually have a pretty clear vision of who should read this book. The record simply stood an unknown man, the yard trembled. How can one place be so calm and at the same time so eerie. Jan Uuspõld read in this summer Mihkel Muti's international man, Andrus Kivirähk's stories and Jaan Kaplinski's piurpääsukese Europe. Reading an audiobook was a first-time experience for me. I've read a little serial story on the radio before, but reading a whole book was new to me. Of course, this opportunity came at a time when there was nothing to do, you sit at home and then it was so nice that there was some opportunity to do something. It's so scary, I don't dare to read anyone.
